ing of law and philosophy and reveals law as the most progressive and experimental force of the Modern Age. Key featuresExplores the connections between law and other disciplines, including literature, the history of philosophy, political theory and geographyProposes several entirely new theories of Deleuze’s relationship to lawContributors are from a range of disciplinary backgrounds and include academics from British, American and Australian law schools  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aLawxPhilosophy. 4aPhilosophy. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh1 aGoodrich, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLefebvre, Alexandre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLincoln, Lissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacLean, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcGee, Kyle, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMcGee, Kyle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoore, Nathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPatton, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPether, Penelope, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhilippopoulos-Mihalopoulos, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSaunders, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchuilenburg, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSutter, Laurent de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z97831107804680 cprintz978074864414840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/97807